  "prompt": "What are the legal precedents related to money laundering cases?",
  "response": "There have been several significant legal precedents in money laundering cases. Some key examples include:\n\n1. United States v. Black (2006)\n- Established criteria for proving intent in money laundering\n- Highlighted importance of proving knowledge of illegal source of funds\n\n2. Bank of Credit and Commerce International (BCCI) case\n- Major international money laundering investigation\n- Set standards for cross-border financial regulations\n\n3. United States v. Santos (2008)\n- Supreme Court clarified definition of \"proceeds\" in money laundering statutes\n- Impacted interpretation of financial crime laws\n\n4. Proceeds of Crime Act (UK, 2002)\n- Comprehensive legal framework for money laundering prosecution\n- Expanded definitions and investigative powers\n\n5. Basel Committee recommendations\n- Established international standards for anti-money laundering compliance\n- Influenced global banking regulations\n\nThese cases and frameworks have shaped modern approaches to investigating and prosecuting money laundering. They've emphasized proving intent, establishing clear legal definitions, and creating robust international cooperation mechanisms.\n\nWould you like me to elaborate on any of these specific precedents?",
